mmand toolkit that takes a new AI coding agent from unknown to fully integrated with the Entire CLI. Each command builds on the previous command's output.\\n    15→\\n    16→## Commands\\n    17→\\n    18→### `/agent-integration research`\\n    19→**Assess compatibility.** Inspect the target agent's CLI, research hook/lifecycle support, create a test script, capture payloads, and produce a structured compatibility report.\\n    20→\\n    21→Detailed instructions: [researcher.md](./researcher.md)\\n    22→\\n    23→### `/agent-integration write-tests`\\n    24→**Write the E2E test suite.** Using the research report's findings, generate E2E test files that validate the agent works end-to-end with Entire's checkpoint/rewind system.\\n    25→\\n    26→Detailed instructions: [test-writer.md](./test-writer.md)\\n    27→\\n    28→### `/agent-integration implement`\\n    29→**Build the agent package via TDD.** Using the research report and E2E tests as the spec, implement the Go agent package with a red-green-refactor cycle.\\n    30→\\n    31→Detailed instructions: [implementer.md](./implementer.md)\\n    32→\\n    33→## Shared Parameters\\n    34→\\n    35→These parameters are shared across all commands. Collect them on first invocation and reuse across subsequent commands.\\n    36→\\n    37→| Parameter | Example | Description |\\n    38→|-----------|---------|-------------|\\n    39→| `AGENT_NAME` | \\\"Windsurf\\\" | Human-readable agent name |\\n    40→| `AGENT_SLUG` | \\\"windsurf\\\" | Lowercase slug for file/directory paths |\\n    41→| `AGENT_BIN` | \\\"windsurf\\\" | CLI binary name |\\n    42→| `LIVE_COMMAND` | \\\"windsurf --project .\\\" | Full command to launch agent |\\n    43→| `EVENTS_OR_UNKNOWN` | \\\"unknown\\\" | Known hook event names, or \\\"unknown\\\" |\\n    44→\\n    45→## Architecture References\\n    46→\\n    47→These documents define the agent integration contract. All commands reference them:\\n    48→\\n    49→- **Implementation guide**: `docs/architecture/agent-guide.md` — Step-by-step code templates, event mapping, testing patterns\\n    50→- **Integration checklist**: `docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md` — Design principles and validation criteria\\n    51→\\n    52→## Command Routing\\n    53→\\n    54→When the user invokes this skill:\\n    55→\\n    56→1. **Parse the argument** after `/agent-integration` to determine which command to run\\n    57→2. **If no argument**, ask which command they want: `research`, `write-tests`, or `implement`\\n    58→3. **If parameters aren't set yet**, collect them before proceeding\\n    59→4. **Load the corresponding prompt file** and follow its instructions\\n    60→\\n    61→### Typical workflow order\\n    62→\\n    63→```\\n    64→/agent-integration research      # Phase 1: Assess compatibility\\n    65→/agent-integration write-tests   # Phase 2: Write test suite\\n    66→/agent-integration implement     # Phase 3: Build via TDD\\n    67→```\\n    68→\\n    69→Each phase can be run independently, but later phases work best with earlier phase outputs available.\\n    70→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"ab7b3740-67ae-42d1-87b8-5c0fd1ffdc21\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-25T23:58:18.969Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"I need to understand two things about Claude Code skills:\\n\\n1. What does the `*` next to a skill name mean in the `/` skill menu?\\n2. How are multi-command skills structured (the `:` subcommand pattern)?\\n\\nLook at these specific areas:\\n- The agent-integration skill: `.claude/skills/agent-integration/` - look at SKILL.md and README.md\\n- The commit-commands skill (which has subcommands like `commit-commands:commit`): find its SKILL.md \\n- Any other skills that use the `:` subcommand pattern (like `claude-md-management:revise-claude-md`, `ralph-loop:help`)\\n- Look at how their SKILL.md files define subcommands vs top-level commands\\n\\nFocus on finding the SKILL.md files and understanding the naming/routin