istant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here's what I found:\\n\\n## The `*` next to `/agent-integration`\\n\\nThe `*` indicates the skill accepts **arguments** (the space-separated subcommands like `research`, `write-tests`, `implement`). Skills without arguments don't get the `*`.\\n\\n## The `:` pattern is a **plugin** feature, not a skill feature\\n\\nLooking at how `commit-commands:commit`, `ralph-loop:help`, etc. work — they're all **plugins**, not local skills:\\n\\n```\\n# Plugin structure (gets colon namespace)\\n~/.claude/plugins/cache/.../commit-commands/\\n  commands/\\n    commit.md          → /commit-commands:commit\\n    commit-push-pr.md  → /commit-commands:commit-push-pr\\n    clean_gone.md      → /commit-commands:clean_gone\\n\\n~/.claude/plugins/cache/.../ralph-loop/\\n  commands/\\n    help.md            → /ralph-loop:help\\n    cancel-ralph.md    → /ralph-loop:cancel-ralph\\n    ralph-loop.md      → /ralph-loop:ralph-loop\\n```\\n\\nEach `.md` file in the `commands/` directory becomes a `plugin-name:command-name` entry. Local skills in `.claude/skills/` **cannot** use the colon pattern.\\n\\n## How to get what you want\\n\\nTo have `/agent-integration` run all 3 phases AND `/agent-integration:research` etc. for individual phases, you'd need to **convert to a plugin**. The structure would be:\\n\\n```\\n.claude-plugin/           # or wherever plugins are defined\\n  plugin.json             # name: \\\"agent-integration\\\"\\n  skills/\\n    agent-integration/\\n      SKILL.md            # Top-level: orchestrates all 3 phases\\n  commands/\\n    research.md           # → /agent-integration:research\\n    write-tests.md        # → /agent-integration:write-tests\\n    implement.md          # → /agent-integration:implement\\n```\\n\\n`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`\\n- **Skills** = complex instructions with SKILL.md frontmatter, support references, live in `skills/<name>/SKILL.md`\\n- **Commands** = simpler single-file p